            <div type="edition" subtype="transcription" ana="b2">
                <p>Ἐγένετο τὸ ἔργον τοῦτω ἐπὶ  <lb/>τοῦ
                        <abbr><abbr>θεοσεβ</abbr><ex>εστάτου</ex></abbr> Ἱλαρίωνος
                            <expan><abbr>ἡγου</abbr><expan>μένου</expan></expan> <expan><abbr>μη</abbr><expan>νὶ</expan></expan> <expan><abbr>Ἀπελ</abbr><expan>λαίου</expan></expan>
                    <lb/><expan><abbr>ἰνδ</abbr><expan>ικτιῶνος</expan></expan> <num value="15">ιε</num>ʹ
                    <expan><abbr>ἔτου</abbr><ex>ς</ex></expan> <num value="397">τϙζʹ</num>. <foreign xml:lang="syc">ܗܕܢ ܘ ܡܪܥܗ ܕܡܪܐ ܨܕܝܩܝܐ ܝܥܘܠܘܢ
                        ܒܓܘܗ</foreign></p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" ana="b2">
                <p>This work was done under the most God-loving Hilarion abbot in the month of
                    Apellaios of the 15th indiction, year 397. "This is the gate of the Lord. The
                    righteous will enter within it."</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" ana="b1 b2">
                <p>The  Christian Palestinian Aramaic component quotes Ps 117:20 [MT 118:20]. The
                    Christian Palestinian Aramaic text is written by two different hands, the later
                    one more skilled than the first. The Greek text contains a date (the month of
                    Apellaios in the fifteenth indiction in the year 397) and the name of the abbot,
                    Ilrion. </p>
            </div>
